payload.user_prompt:
Propose 4 distinct strategies to beat the baseline.

PROBLEM: Euclidean Travelling Salesman Problem: given N cities as (x, y) points, find the shortest closed tour visiting every city exactly once. Score = total tour length (lower is better).
INSTANCE: 60 cities, uniform random in [0,1000]^2, seed=42
SCOPE: {"objective": "Minimize the total Euclidean tour length for a 60-city TSP instance (seed=42) below the nearest-neighbor baseline of 7489.18 by applying advanced heuristics or metaheuristics within budget and time constraints.", "success_criteria": {"target_improvement_pct": 18.0, "rationale": "The operator suggests 18% improvement, yielding a target tour length of ~6141.1. For 60 cities, well-tuned algorithms (2-opt, 3-opt, Lin-Kernighan, or OR-opt) routinely achieve 15-25% improvement over nearest-neighbor. An 18% target is achievable within 10s per experiment for N=60, as the search space is tractable and modern local search converges quickly at this scale."}, "constraints": ["Maximum 5 optimization rounds total", "Maximum $2 USD total API/compute budget", "Maximum 10 seconds wall-clock time per individual experiment", "Must visit all 60 cities exactly once and return to start (valid Hamiltonian cycle)", "City coordinates fixed to seed=42 uniform random in [0,1000]^2 \u2014 no instance modification allowed", "Tour length must be computed as sum of Euclidean distances between consecutive cities"], "stop_conditions": ["Tour length reaches or falls below 6141.1 (18% improvement over baseline)", "All 5 rounds have been exhausted", "Total spend reaches $2 USD", "A round produces no improvement over the previous best solution (convergence detected)", "Any single experiment exceeds 10 seconds execution time (discard result, count round)"], "reasoning": "For N=60, nearest-neighbor heuristics leave substantial room for improvement since they greedily construct tours without backtracking. Classical 2-opt alone typically recovers 10-15% on random instances; 3-opt or Lin-Kernighan style moves can push to 18-22%. The 10s time limit is generous for N=60 \u2014 even exhaustive 2-opt runs in milliseconds at this scale, leaving room for multiple restarts or 3-opt passes. With 5 rounds available, a staged approach (2-opt \u2192 3-opt/OR-opt \u2192 LKH-style perturbation) is feasible within the $2 budget. The 18% target is thus realistic and well-calibrated for this instance size and constraint set."}

Each strategy must be implementable in pure Python within the time limit.
Return JSON:
{
  "hypotheses": [
    {"name": "<short name>", "strategy": "<algorithm family>",
      "hypothesis": "<falsifiable claim: doing X will improve over baseline because Y>",
      "risk": "<main reason this could fail>"}
  ]
}

